'''Noki Shrine''' (のきじんじゃ) is a {{ill|lt=Shinto shrine|Q845945|WD=Q845945|1=Shinto shrine}} in Nogi-chō, {{ill|lt=Yasugi|Q851114|WD=Q851114|1=Yasugi, Shimane}}, {{ill|lt=Shimane Prefecture|Q132751|WD=Q132751|1=Shimane Prefecture}}. Its former rank under the {{ill|lt=Modern shrine ranking system|Q712534|WD=Q712534|1=Modern system of ranked Shinto shrines}} was prefectural shrine.

=== Enshrined deities ===
Current deities are as follows.
*{{ill|WD=Q10940685|lt=Ame-no-Hohi|Q10940685|WD=Q10940685|WD=Q10940685|lt=Ame-no-Hohi-no-Mikoto|1=Ame no Hohi}}
*{{ill|lt=Ōkuninushi|Q276944|WD=Q276944|lt=Ōnamuchi-no-Mikoto|1=Ōkuninushi}}
*{{ill|WD=Q8009611|lt=Kotoshironushi|Q8009611|WD=Q8009611|WD=Q8009611|lt=Kotoshironushi-no-Mikoto|1=Kotoshironushi-no-Mikoto}}
In the entry for Noki station in Ou District of the ''{{ill|lt=Izumo-no-Kuni Fudoki|Q11395858|WD=Q11395858|1=Izumo no Kuni Fudoki}}'', Noki Ōkami appears. The original deity is considered to have been this Noki Ōkami, and there is a theory that Noki Ōkami and Ame-no-Hohi-no-Mikoto are the same deity<ref name="bunken2">''Gods of Japan (7)'', p.40.</ref>.

=== History ===
It is identified with “Noki-sha,” a Shrine Bureau shrine in the Ou District section of ''Izumo-no-Kuni Fudoki,'' and with “Noki Shrine” in Ou District, Izumo Province, in the ''{{ill|lt=Engishiki Jinmyōchō|Q11064932|WD=Q11064932|1=Engishiki Jinmyōchō}}''; but there is also a theory identifying it with “Ame-no-Hohi-no-Mikoto Shrine” in Nogi District in the same text. Between this shrine and Kunitsu Daimyōjin in Kisa village (now {{ill|UNKNOWN|lt=Shibusa Shrine|1=UNKNOWN}}), there were disputes over candidate status twice: in the {{ill|lt=Shōtoku (Japan)|Q1193848|WD=Q1193848|lt=Shōtoku|1=Shōtoku (era)}} era and early {{ill|lt=Meiji|Q3125096|WD=Q3125096|1=Meiji era}}<ref>''Gods of Japan (7)'', p.42.</ref>.

According to ''{{ill|lt=Nihon Sandai Jitsuroku|Q1052981|WD=Q1052981|1=Nihon Sandai Jitsuroku}}'', the {{ill|lt=court rank for shrines|Q11591025|WD=Q11591025|1=Shinkai (divine rank)}} granted to Nogi deity was Junior Fifth Upper in {{ill|lt=867|Q23899|WD=Q23899|1=Dizzy (series)}} ({{ill|lt=Jōgan|Q1075635|WD=Q1075635|1=Jōgan}} 9) and Senior Fifth Lower in {{ill|lt=871|Q23903|WD=Q23903|1=Tworki, Siedlce County}} (Jōgan 13). However, it is unclear whether these were granted to Noki Shrine or to Ame-no-Hohi-no-Mikoto Shrine<ref name="bunken2" />.

When shrine buildings were lost in a fire in {{ill|lt=1611|Q6768|WD=Q6768|1=1611}} ({{ill|lt=Keichō|Q1328185|WD=Q1328185|1=Keichō}} 16), old records were also lost. In early modern times it was revered as the sōsha of Nogi District. It was ranked gōsha in {{ill|lt=Meiji 4|Q11512280|WD=Q11512280|1=Meiji – year 4}}, then promoted to prefectural shrine in Meiji 6 ({{ill|lt=1873|Q7757|WD=Q7757|1=1873}}).

=== Ancient historic sites ===
In the precinct is the Noki Shrine site, considered to be dwelling remains from the {{ill|lt=Yayoi period|Q207858|WD=Q207858|1=Yayoi period}} to {{ill|lt=Kofun period|Q459939|WD=Q459939|1=Kofun period}}. Nearby are several {{ill|lt=round tumuli|Q11394747|WD=Q11394747|1=Round Kofun}}, including Noki Shrine Okuin Kofun.

